04482nam a22004815i 9780226871844DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20092009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226871844  a(DE-B1597)524421  a(OCoLC)458586518  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQ143.H9bD388 2009 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a508.0921 aWalls, Laura Dassow, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Passage to Cosmos :bAlexander von Humboldt and the Shaping of America /cLaura Dassow Walls. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b22 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Romancing the Ruby-Crowned Kinglet -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue: Humboldt’s Bridge -- t1. Confluences -- t2. Passage to America, 1799–1804 -- t3. Manifest Destinies -- t4. “All are alike designed for freedom”: Humboldt on Race and Slavery -- t5. The Community of Cosmos -- t6. The Face of Planet America -- tEpilogue: Recalling Cosmos -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplorer, scientist, writer, and humanist, Alexander von Humboldt was the most famous intellectual of the age that began with Napoleon and ended with Darwin. With Cosmos, the book that crowned his career, Humboldt offered to the world his vision of humans and nature as integrated halves of a single whole. In it, Humboldt espoused the idea that, while the universe of nature exists apart from human purpose, its beauty and order, the very idea of the whole it composes, are human achievements: cosmos comes into being in the dance of world and mind, subject and object, science and poetry. Humboldt’s science laid the foundations for ecology and inspired the theories of his most important scientific disciple, Charles Darwin. In the United States, his ideas shaped the work of Emerson, Thoreau, Poe, and Whitman. They helped spark the American environmental movement through followers like John Muir and George Perkins Marsh. And they even bolstered efforts to free the slaves and honor the rights of Indians. Laura Dassow Walls here traces Humboldt’s ideas for Cosmos to his 1799 journey to the Americas, where he first experienced the diversity of nature and of the world’s peoples—and envisioned a new cosmopolitanism that would link ideas, disciplines, and nations into a global web of knowledge and cultures. In reclaiming Humboldt’s transcultural and transdisciplinary project, Walls situates America in a lively and contested field of ideas, actions, and interests, and reaches beyond to a new worldview that integrates the natural and social sciences, the arts, and the humanities. To the end of his life, Humboldt called himself “half an American,” but ironically his legacy has largely faded in the United States. The Passage to Cosmos will reintroduce this seminal thinker to a new audience and return America to its rightful place in the story of his life, work, and enduring legacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aSciencexHistoryx19th century. 0aSciencexHistoryy19th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aamerica, american, history, historical, academic, scholarly, research, cosmology, humanist, science, scientist, explorer, writer, intellectual, time period, era, napoleon, darwin, humans, humanity, nature, natural world, human, ecology, poetry, ecologist, united states, influential, emerson, thoreau, whitman, humanities, social sciences, interdisciplinary, transdisciplinary, 19th century.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226871844423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226871844/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles